<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-04-24T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-04-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="138" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d138">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">792.94/117</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Navy Department</gloss> to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                            </hi><note n="84" xml:id="d138fn1">Handed by Capt. Roscoe E. Schuirmann,
                                of the Office of Naval Operations, to the Chief of the Division of
                                Far Eastern Affairs (Hamilton) on April 25; noted by the Secretary
                                of State.</note>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-04-24">April 24,
                                1941</date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>The following message was received from the Commander in Chief Asiatic
                                Fleet<note n="85" xml:id="d138fn2">Adm. Thomas C. Hart,
                                U.S.N.</note> this date:</p>
                        <p>To prevent spread Nipponese influence in Thailand and Brooke-Popham<note n="86" xml:id="d138fn3">Air Marshal Sir Robert Brooke-Popham,
                                British Commander in Chief, Far East.</note> during Singapore
                            conference urges our Government join in mutual diplomatic <hi rend="italic">démarche.</hi>
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>